 PhD research that dealt with changing discourses of distress and powerlessness in post-Soviet Latvia by relating her findings to the concept of social exclusion. The analysis of the data (36 audio-recorded life-story interviews with Latvian sufferers from psychological distress and 40 interviews with mental health care specialists) will be brought to a comparative focus by pursuing a cross-cultural study together with Prof. H&amp;auml;nninen (Finland) and exploring the ways in which distress in two North European countries is related to social exclusion and the accompanying lack of support. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>In the perspective of the structural strain theory Latvia, along with other post-socialist countries that have undergone a rapid social change since the early 1990s, appears a classic case of a too weakly integrated society. In this respect, a comparison with Finland is likely to reveal the patterns of psychosocial distress characterising societies with varying degrees of integration. The study aims to illuminate each society?s system of values and to reveal those patterns of social exclusion that the two societies might share. The findings will contribute to understanding of regional variations that effective social policies within the EU context should take into account.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2006-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>27139</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">PTA-026-27-1038</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D21C7A3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Anthropology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D21C7A3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr